Ubi—continuatur, “who suffers under such an accumulation of [uninterrupted] misery.'' We have followed the example of Klotz in making these words a. part of the verse. Most of the editors suppose the words to be Cicero’s‚ and F. A. Wolf translates them, “in which passage P. so piteously bemoans his misery;’' but this does not at all agree with what follows (si quidem homo esset, &c.). Of the two we should prefer Kiihner's suggestion, who would make the words a part of the next sentence, vide, ἃς. The sense would then be, “Notwithstanding this accumulation of misery, he does not utter any lamentations,’' &c.
